{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PVW7xnn9FTQUouT38pHqRT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup:\n\n1. `canary-stable` Ingress: Routes `canary.example.com` to `stable-echo` service for both `/health` (Prefix) and `/` (Exact). This is the main/base ingress.\n\n2. `canary-canary` Ingress: A canary ingress with annotations `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary: \"true\"`, `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary-by-header: X-Canary`, and `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary-by-header-value: always`. \n\nIt routes to `canary-echo` service, which looks correct. There's also a decoy `canary-alt` ingress with `canary-by-header-value: beta` that routes to `stable-echo` instead. The `canary-canary` ingress has the right annotations and target service in theory, but the issue might be that the nginx ingress controller's canary feature requires the canary ingress to be properly linked to the stable ingress.\n\nLooking at the configuration more carefully, both ingresses have the same host `canary.example.com`, which is correct. The stable ingress defines `/health` with Prefix matching and `/` with Exact matching, while the canary ingress only has `/` with Exact matching. This should work for the root path test. The nginx canary behavior should route requests with the `X-Canary: always` header to the canary service, and requests without it to the stable service.\n\nThe `canary-alt` ingress on a different host shouldn't interfere. Let me run the tests to see what's actually happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1483,"cache_read_input_tokens":30657,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1483},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"sess